Answer 1:-
`<!DOCTYPE html>` is not an HTML tag; it is a Document Type Declaration (doctype). Placed at the beginning of an HTML document, it specifies the version of HTML being used. The doctype informs web browsers how to interpret and render the content correctly, as different versions of HTML have different rules. `<!DOCTYPE html>` specifically denotes HTML5, the latest HTML version. Using the correct doctype declaration ensures cross-browser compatibility and consistent rendering. Without it or with an incorrect declaration, browsers may use different rendering modes, resulting in inconsistent appearance and behavior of the web page.
Answer 2:-
Semantic tags in HTML are specific elements that carry meaningful information about the structure and content of a web page. These tags describe the purpose and meaning of the enclosed content, making it easier for search engines, accessibility tools, and developers to understand and interpret the page's structure.

Semantic tags include elements like `<header>`, `<nav>`, `<section>`, `<article>`, `<aside>`, `<footer>`, `<main>`, `<figure>`, `<figcaption>`, and more. Each tag represents a specific section or type of content within a web page.

The importance of semantic tags lies in their ability to improve the accessibility and search engine optimization (SEO) of a website. Search engines can better understand the page's content and hierarchy, leading to improved indexing and higher visibility in search results. Additionally, semantic tags assist screen readers and other accessibility tools in properly conveying the structure and meaning of the page to users with disabilities.

Using semantic tags also helps with code organization and maintenance. By utilizing appropriate tags, developers can create well-structured HTML documents that are easier to read, navigate, and modify, promoting code reusability and reducing maintenance efforts.


Answer 3:-
HTML tags and elements are related concepts but have distinct meanings. 

HTML tags are the markup characters used to define the structure and presentation of elements within an HTML document. They are enclosed within angle brackets, such as `<tagname>`. Tags provide instructions to the browser on how to render and interpret the content.

On the other hand, HTML elements consist of the opening and closing tags along with the content placed between them. They represent the building blocks of an HTML document and define the structure and meaning of the content. Elements consist of both the opening and closing tags, such as `<tagname>content</tagname>`.


