    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <div class="music-player">
    <audio id="audio-player" controls>
      <source src="path_to_audio_file.mp3" type="audio/mpeg">
      Your browser does not support the audio element.
    </audio>
  </div>
</body>
</html>

Answer 8:-
The `<img>` tag is used to embed standalone images in an HTML document. It requires the `src` attribute to specify the image file's source and the `alt` attribute to provide alternative text for accessibility. It is primarily used for visual content without any additional context or description.

The `<figure>` tag, on the other hand, is used to group together related content, typically an image, and its associated caption or description. It provides a semantic container to convey that the content within it is a single unit. The `<figure>` tag can include an `<img>` tag along with a `<figcaption>` tag to provide a caption or description for the image.

Answer 9:
In HTML, a tag represents an element or a structure within the markup, while an attribute provides additional information or modifies the behavior of a tag. Here's a breakdown of the differences:

HTML Tag:
A tag is an element in HTML that defines the structure or content of a document. Tags are enclosed in angle brackets (`<` and `>`). For example, `<h1>`, `<p>`, and `<div>` are all examples of HTML tags. Tags can be self-closing, like `<img>` or `<br>`, or they can have opening and closing tags, like `<div></div>`.

HTML Attribute:
An attribute is used to provide additional information or modify the behavior of an HTML tag. Attributes are specified within the opening tag of an element and consist of a name-value pair. For example, in `<a href="https://www.example.com">`, the `href` attribute provides the URL that the link points to.

Global Attributes:
Global attributes are attributes that can be applied to any HTML element. Some common global attributes include:

1. `class`: Specifies one or more class names for an element, allowing it to be styled using CSS or targeted by JavaScript.
2. `id`: Specifies a unique identifier for an element, which can be used for styling or scripting purposes.
3. `style`: Defines inline CSS styles to be applied to the element.
4. `title`: Specifies additional information about an element, typically displayed as a tooltip when hovering over the element.
5. `data-*`: Allows the storage of custom data attributes for an element, which can be accessed through JavaScript.

These attributes can be used with various HTML tags to provide additional functionality or styling to elements in an HTML document.

